item.description:
This week our guest will be Windows PowerShell MVP Jeffery Hicks to talk about his latest training DVD from Train Signal, Windows PowerShell Fundamentals. Jeff will give us some great tips and techniques for PowerShell beginners, and we&rsquo;ll get his take on PowerShell v3 as well.
&ndash; Update @ 9:08AM &ndash;
We forgot that Jeff has an EVEN NEWER and BETTER course out that builds on the previous one. It&rsquo;s all about managing Windows Server with PowerShell and we&rsquo;ll be covering it as well.

On tonight&quot;™s show (1/13/11 @ 9:30pm EST right here on Ustream!), we&quot;™ll be talking to Jim Christopher, aka @beefarino about his newest project: StudioShell. As you can read on his blog post announcement,
&ldquo;StudioShell is a deeply integrated PowerShell host available inside of Visual Studio 2010 and 2008. It&quot;™s goal is to fundamentally change the way you interact with your IDE and your code. &quot;
[youtube=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TkBzXlrlC5w&amp;w=448&amp;h=252&amp;hd=1] StudioShell - Extending Visual Studio with PowerShell Be sure to drop by the Ustream channel tonight so that you can post questions for Jim and interact with your fellow PowerShellers!

A Podcast about Windows PowerShell. Listen:
In This Episode {#tiap}
Tonight on the PowerScripting Podcast, we talk to Trevor Sullivan about working with WMI events in PowerShell
News PowerGUI Pro and PowerGUI 2.3 are out!{#v2vp}
Tampa - Jan 15th - SQL Saturday #62, featuring SQLVariant talking about &ldquo;SQL Smackdown: SSIS vs. PowerShell{#hbs3}&rdquo;, and The Scripting Guy with &ldquo;Windows PowerShell 2.0 Best Practices for DBA&rsquo;s{#w_5o}&rdquo;
The PowerGUI Challenge winners have been announced{#kpfz}Â Don Jones is teaching a [5-day &ldquo;PowerShell Retreat&rdquo; class][5]{#z2oe} in June, 2011

We received this from someone on the PowerShell team at Microsoft today. Made us feel mighty fine. 🙂
&ldquo;I know running the Podcast is often a thankless job, but you guys are nailing it. It is absolutely one of the highlights of the PowerShell community &ldquo;“ you guys should be very proud for what you&quot;™ve accomplished.&rdquo;
As always, we do love hearing from all of our listeners. Whatever you have to say, please let us know!

Mark from San Jose California writes:
I have a powershell script currently running on a Windows2003 server. It acts upon an Access DB (I know &ldquo;“ not ideal but it is the only way I could figure out how to add / manipulate records in a Sharepoint list ( the Access DB is just link tables from SharePoint)) &ldquo;“ via the following Conn String: $ConnString = &ldquo;Provider=Microsoft.Jet.OLEDB.4.0;Data Source=$mdb&rdquo;
When I attempt to run in this our new Windows2008 server, I run into the following error: Exception calling &ldquo;Open&rdquo; with &ldquo;0&rdquo; argument(s): &ldquo;The &lsquo;Microsoft.
